    },
    {
      "id": "NNryEhHI7lEDpyxbrA1yr",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1293.3667587796294,
      "y": 10266.391429728252,
      "width": 2192.651611328125,
      "height": 2565,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b25",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1359697796,
      "version": 4287,
      "versionNonce": 1997228140,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1767711317830,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Booting up a Docker container is a time consuming task, then compiling the code then running the code\nthen evaluting test cases there are lot of steps involved and during a contest people don't think that\nLeetcode infrastructure can go down they just keep on making the submissions that means we can't allow\nour App servers to bombard submissions on our Evaluator machines\nbecause if they keep on bombaring our Evaluator machines they can also crash even if we horizontally scaled\nA good solution comes in our mind is AutoScaling\nProblem with AutoScaling -> we will have lot of machines coming up because this is pretty heavy operation\neven if we rate limit a particular user lets say we rate limit our user in 1 minute user is allowed to put only\n5 submissions lets say in our contest only there are 1 Million users\n\nso 5 Million submission per minute 5 million evaluation\nwhere we need to create\nnew docker Container\nwe have to load the code\ncompile the code\nrun the code\nmatch the test cases\ncreate the evaluation report\n\nlot of thigs we need to do some people are sending C++ code okay that will be fast, some people are sending\nPython code that will take 5X time so we can't not even rely on rate limiting properly because there are lot of\nusers\n\nDefinetely we can keep our evaluator machines horizontally scaled  but we need to setup a mechanism with which\nthis whole asynchronous communication will work. Because we can't allow our App servers to bombard our Evaluator\nmachines\n\nthats where the asses of using Async communication will come into the picture because we are not in a hurry\nto show the users there final report, we have to collect the submission from them. We have to evaluate them\nas fast as possible but we are not in the boudation that we have to just send it back \n\nApart from that every submission will be evaluated on different Docker container\n\nWhy every submission on diff docker Container?\nBecause If we are evaluating 5 submission on same docker container and one of them is fork bomb it can impact\nother submissions as well so every submission will be having its own docker container and every docker container\nwill be having diff image based on the language that we want to use for C++ diff docker image for Python there \nwill be diff image\n\n\nHow can we avoid our Application servers to bombard our evaluator machines -> for that we need a mechanism bcz this\nis async our users are not blocked on us. In an async mechanism best part is that we can park our request \n\nwhat is meaning by parking -> parking a req means not every req will evaluate immediately, we can one by one based on our\nload capacity evaluate request the moment we realize our system needs parking of requests the best way to use some kind\nof message broker like RabbitMQ, AWS SQS, Redis\n\nMessage broker -> It is a infrastructure where we have lot of Queues. these queues are running over Message Broker server\n\nQueue -> Datastructure which can help us to park our request based on different priorities, if the priority is time based \npriority then Normal Queues are way to go with\nif priority is something else then we need to create custom priority Queue like two user one is paid one is free both have \nsubmitted the code in that case we are bound to evaluate paid user first, so in that case we will define priority queue. like\nall the paid user request will go to queue1 that will be higher priority and free user request will go to queue2 that will be\nlower priority.\n\nlets say our queue can handle 13 job and we have 12 VM then 13 job need to wait untill 1 VM is free to process the req.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Booting up a Docker container is a time consuming task, then compiling the code then running the code\nthen evaluting test cases there are lot of steps involved and during a contest people don't think that\nLeetcode infrastructure can go down they just keep on making the submissions that means we can't allow\nour App servers to bombard submissions on our Evaluator machines\nbecause if they keep on bombaring our Evaluator machines they can also crash even if we horizontally scaled\nA good solution comes in our mind is AutoScaling\nProblem with AutoScaling -> we will have lot of machines coming up because this is pretty heavy operation\neven if we rate limit a particular user lets say we rate limit our user in 1 minute user is allowed to put only\n5 submissions lets say in our contest only there are 1 Million users\n\nso 5 Million submission per minute 5 million evaluation\nwhere we need to create\nnew docker Container\nwe have to load the code\ncompile the code\nrun the code\nmatch the test cases\ncreate the evaluation report\n\nlot of thigs we need to do some people are sending C++ code okay that will be fast, some people are sending\nPython code that will take 5X time so we can't not even rely on rate limiting properly because there are lot of\nusers\n\nDefinetely we can keep our evaluator machines horizontally scaled  but we need to setup a mechanism with which\nthis whole asynchronous communication will work. Because we can't allow our App servers to bombard our Evaluator\nmachines\n\nthats where the asses of using Async communication will come into the picture because we are not in a hurry\nto show the users there final report, we have to collect the submission from them. We have to evaluate them\nas fast as possible but we are not in the boudation that we have to just send it back \n\nApart from that every submission will be evaluated on different Docker container\n\nWhy every submission on diff docker Container?\nBecause If we are evaluating 5 submission on same docker container and one of them is fork bomb it can impact\nother submissions as well so every submission will be having its own docker container and every docker container\nwill be having diff image based on the language that we want to use for C++ diff docker image for Python there \nwill be diff image\n\n\nHow can we avoid our Application servers to bombard our evaluator machines -> for that we need a mechanism bcz this\nis async our users are not blocked on us. In an async mechanism best part is that we can park our request \n\nwhat is meaning by parking -> parking a req means not every req will evaluate immediately, we can one by one based on our\nload capacity evaluate request the moment we realize our system needs parking of requests the best way to use some kind\nof message broker like RabbitMQ, AWS SQS, Redis\n\nMessage broker -> It is a infrastructure where we have lot of Queues. these queues are running over Message Broker server\n\nQueue -> Datastructure which can help us to park our request based on different priorities, if the priority is time based \npriority then Normal Queues are way to go with\nif priority is something else then we need to create custom priority Queue like two user one is paid one is free both have \nsubmitted the code in that case we are bound to evaluate paid user first, so in that case we will define priority queue. like\nall the paid user request will go to queue1 that will be higher priority and free user request will go to queue2 that will be\nlower priority.\n\nlets say our queue can handle 13 job and we have 12 VM then 13 job need to wait untill 1 VM is free to process the req.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
